  "prompt": "How does white label banking in Europe work?",
  "response": "White label banking in Europe allows financial institutions or non-bank companies to offer banking services under their own brand, while the underlying infrastructure and operations are provided by an established bank. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Core Characteristics:\n- A partner bank provides core banking technology and regulatory compliance\n- The white label partner brands and markets banking services as their own\n- Customers interact with the partner brand, not the underlying bank\n\n2. Common Models:\n- Digital-only banking platforms\n- Retail companies offering financial services\n- Fintech startups creating banking products\n- Telecommunication companies expanding into financial services\n\n3. Regulatory Framework:\n- Governed by European Banking Authority regulations\n- Must comply with EU financial services directives\n- Requires appropriate licensing and authorization\n\n4. Typical Services Offered:\n- Current accounts\n- Debit/credit cards\n- Payment processing\n- Online/mobile banking\n- Savings products\n\n5. Key Benefits:\n- Faster market entry for new financial service providers\n- Lower infrastructure investment\n- Reduced regulatory complexity\n- Enhanced customer experience\n- Innovative financial product development\n\n6. Examples:\n- Numerous fintech companies in UK, Germany, France using white label banking\n- Tech companies like Apple and Google offering financial services\n\nThe model provides flexibility and innovation in European banking services.",
